hands_on_practices.solution:
We seek the quotient norm 
$$\|[f]\|=\inf_{c\in\Bbb R}\|\,t^2+c\|_{L^2([0,1])}
=\inf_{c}\sqrt{\int_0^1(t^2+c)^2\,dt}.$$
1. Compute the squared norm as a function of $c$:
$$J(c)=\int_0^1(t^2+c)^2\,dt
=\int_0^1\bigl(t^4+2c\,t^2+c^2\bigr)dt
=\int_0^1t^4\,dt+2c\int_0^1t^2\,dt+c^2\int_0^1dt
=\frac15+\frac{2c}{3}+c^2.$$
2. Find the minimizing $c$ by setting $J'(c)=0$:
$$J'(c)=\frac{2}{3}+2c=0\quad\Longrightarrow\quad c=-\frac13.$$
3. Compute the minimum value:
$$J\!\bigl(-\tfrac13\bigr)
=\frac15+2\bigl(-\tfrac13\bigr)\frac13+\bigl(-\tfrac13\bigr)^2
=\frac15-\frac{2}{9}+\frac{1}{9}
=\frac{1}{5}-\frac{1}{9}
=\frac{9-5}{45}
=\frac{4}{45}.$$
4. Hence the quotient norm is
$$\|[f]\|=\sqrt{\frac{4}{45}}
=\frac{2}{\sqrt{45}}
=\frac{2}{3\sqrt5}
=\frac{2\sqrt5}{15}.$$
